	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=259967><span id= >pinchers</span></a><br><span id=notbold>8 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Now this is what really burns my butt and I will tell you why.&nbsp;&nbsp;We did an LDoN with 2 Clerics,  Yeah 2 and you would think that NOONE would die with 2 clerics. What happened was that one of the clerics refused to heal anybody using this argument of the Roleplaying BS.   this argument is a CROCK.  These characters were designed with certain strengths and weakeness and to Roleplay a  certain character effectively is to find those characters Strengths and use them.  You dont make a cleric an archer.  If you want to do Archery MAKE A RANGER but play your character the way they were meant to be played.  If you are a Wizard and you want to tank, make a new Warrior class  character but dont be a liability in your group and get your group mates DEAD because you want to be 'toopid and have your Wizard tank for your group because you are &quot;roleplaying&quot; !  Now that is being dramatic but the fact is that this is a game and the characters are limited by the game design.  Every class of character gets skills they excell in and some lesser skills which they can use but are not very effective, such as a Ranger can heal BUT he shouldnt be the primary healer in a group with his 100pt heals just because he wants to &quot;ROLEPLAY&quot; a healer.  For a Ranger to call himself  Ranger/Healer who is &quot;roleplaying&quot; just isnt going to convince anybody that they want that man in their group healing.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Nov 22 17:44:21 2003</em></p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
