	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=16386&mid=103987949138988>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=16386&mid=103987949138988>RE: The endless bow debate</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=16386&mid=103987949138988#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sat, Dec 14th 10:49 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=157153><span id=Guru>aanil</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>28 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;As a Ranger who doesn't roleplay.  I want other melees to have good bows.  The reason for this is game dynamics...<br>  If I'm pulling, how does the MT get aggro before the mob clobbers me?  The best tank class, Warrior, has to use a ranged weapon.  A tank should have a high range, low delay bow for pulling and establishing aggro.  Just because they have spells does not mean a knight class should overlook the same use.  Any aggro the MT can get should not be ignored, and a good bow is effective long before the mob gets into casting range.<br>  Yes, with a monk puller or on an especially nasty mob, the tank will probably use a ranged item purely for stats (unless tagging is needed).  But as a ranger, I appreciate a tank who keeps his archery skill up, has a good bow, and knows when to use it.  Ideally, a tank's bow also provides stats useful for their class, alleviating the need for item switches.<br><br>  Rogues also can make good use of bows, and not just for pulling.  Often a rogue has to delay his melee attack to avoid drawing aggro early in the fight.  With a high delay, high ratio bow, that time can be spent dishing damage from a distance instead of hiding in the shadows.  And every once in a while, things get ugly and everybody has to stay out of the melee range of a rooted mob while the healers med.  Four melees with good bows can still do decent damage.<br><br>  As for this bow specifically, the delay is a little high for a tank, but the range is decent, and the damage should make up for it.  The stats are passable, especially for a knight class.  It wouldn't be a major upgrade for me, so I would have to ask the tanks what they had before accepting it &quot;because I'm a ranger&quot;.  Awarding it to me may not be to the best advantage.<br>  Rangers get the really hard pulls...  Nobody will tell a monk<br>&quot;There's a wandering mob somewhere on the other side of this zone with a really good drop.  If we go out there, we'll die.  Go over there, track him down, pull him all the way across the zone, and try to avoid adds on the way, cuz we can't handle more than one, maybe two. Some of the mobs out there HT for 1k+, so watch yourself.  And umm.. This mob we want can't be snared, rooted, slowed, stunned, or mezzed, and moves at almost SOW speed.  Doubles for 300+, too.&quot;<br><br>When the ranger comes back with the mob right behind him, a snared add on the way, and 400hp left, he'll be prayin' that the Warrior knows how to shoot and can hit several times for decent damage.  The celestial heal the cleric is casting just ain't gunna cover this one...</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>[65 Forest Stalker] Aanil &lt;Infinit&gt;<br></td></tr>
